It occurs that the date was in integer format. To clean this, we need to
convert this to the date format. We first note that the date format
begin on 30 Dec 1899 and it's definitely safe to assume our dataset
starts after that date.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{transactionData}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{DATE }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(transactionData}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{DATE, }\AttributeTok{origin =} \StringTok{"1899{-}12{-}30"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(transactionData)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}

As we can see above, the word ``g'' happens to be the most appeared,
however this character was part of the weight of the product and was not
remove during the deletion of digits. Thus, we may ignore ``g''. This
makes ``Chips'' as the most frequent words in PROD\_NAME column. Going
through the first two pages, one will eventually found that there is
``Salsa'' product. This is not part of our use later, so we shall remove
it.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Remove salsa products}
\NormalTok{transactionData }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.data.table}\NormalTok{(transactionData)}
\NormalTok{transactionData[, SALSA }\SpecialCharTok{:}\ErrorTok{=} \FunctionTok{grepl}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"salsa"}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{tolower}\NormalTok{(PROD\_NAME))] }
\NormalTok{transactionData }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ transactionData[SALSA }\SpecialCharTok{==} \ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, ][, SALSA }\SpecialCharTok{:}\ErrorTok{=} \ConstantTok{NULL}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

So now we have cleaned the date format and removed non-chips products,
we proceed to check the numerical values to seek for missing values or
outliers.

Fortunately, there is no missing values in our dataset. However, judging
from the interquartile range and min-max values of PROD\_QTY and
TOT\_SALES, we might have a potential outlier. Let's investigate when
the purchased quantity equals 200.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{transactionData[PROD\_QTY }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}

## 2: 2019-05-20       226         226000 226210        4
##                           PROD_NAME PROD_QTY TOT_SALES
## 1: Dorito Corn Chp     Supreme 380g      200       650
## 2: Dorito Corn Chp     Supreme 380g      200       650
\end{verbatim}

We found that 2 transactions where the quantity equals 200 by the same
customer (LYTL\_CARD\_NBR). Let's check if this customer had made any
other transactions for chips.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{transactionData[LYLTY\_CARD\_NBR }\SpecialCharTok{==} \StringTok{"226000"}\NormalTok{,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

## 2: Dorito Corn Chp     Supreme 380g      200       650

There were no other purchases made by the customer, so this customer is
not an ordinary customer. It can be that the purchases made were for
commercial. Thus, we will remove the Loyalty card number form our
analysis.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# we can either filter by LYLTY\_CARD\_NBR!=\textquotesingle{}226000\textquotesingle{} or PROD\_QTY\textless{}200, both will do the work.}
\NormalTok{transactionData }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ transactionData[LYLTY\_CARD\_NBR }\SpecialCharTok{!=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}226000\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

That looks much better. Now, let's look at the number of transaction
lines over time to see if there are any obvious data issues such as
missing data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Count transactions by date}
\NormalTok{transactionbyDate }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ transactionData }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(DATE) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{count}\NormalTok{(DATE) }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

There are only 364 rows which means 1 date is missing. Let's try to find
the missing date. To do this, we create a sequence of dates of 365 days
from 01-07-2018 to 30-06-2019. Then, we merge (left-join) the sequence
with transactionbyDate to check the date with missing values

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Creating the sequence of date}
\NormalTok{daySeq }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{seq.Date}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"2018{-}07{-}01"}\NormalTok{), }\FunctionTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"2019{-}06{-}30"}\NormalTok{), }\AttributeTok{by=}\StringTok{"days"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{daySeq }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.data.table}\NormalTok{(daySeq)}
\FunctionTok{setnames}\NormalTok{(daySeq, }\StringTok{"date"}\NormalTok{)}
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# left{-}joining daySeq and transactionbyDate}
\NormalTok{transactionbyDate }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.data.table}\NormalTok{(transactionbyDate)}
\NormalTok{day\_n }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ daySeq }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{left\_join}\NormalTok{(transactionbyDate, }\AttributeTok{date =}\NormalTok{ DATE)}
\NormalTok{day\_n[}\FunctionTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{is.na}\NormalTok{(day\_n}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{n)),]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
##          DATE  n
## 1: 2018-12-25 NA
\end{verbatim}

\texttt{all.x\ =\ TRUE} (in other words, a left join) which means take
all the rows in \texttt{transactionData} and find rows with matching
values in shared columns and then joining the details in these rows to
the \texttt{x} or the first mentioned table.

\hypertarget{data-analysis-on-customer-section}{%
\subsection{Data Analysis on customer
section}\label{data-analysis-on-customer-section}}

Now that the data is ready for analysis, we can define some metrics of
interest to the client:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Who spends the most on chips (total sales), describing customers by
  lifestage and how premium their general purchasing behaviour is
\item
  How many customers are in each segment
\item
  How many chips are bought per customer by segment- What's the average
  chip price by customer segment
\end{itemize}

We could also ask our data team for more information. Examples are: -
The customer's total spend over the period and total spend for each
transaction to understand what proportion of their grocery spend is on
chips - Proportion of customers in each customer segment overall to
compare against the mix of customers who purchase chips

Let's start with calculating total sales by LIFESTAGE and
PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER and plotting the split by these segments to describe
which customer segment contribute most to chip sales.

Older families and young families in general buy more chips per customer

Let's also investigate the average price per unit chips bought for each
customer segment as this is also a driver of total sales.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Average price per unit by LIFESTAGE and PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER }

\CommentTok{\# Over to you! Calculate and plot the average price per unit sold (average sale price) by those two customer dimensions. }
\CommentTok{\# Create table of customer and sales per unit}
\CommentTok{\# First we summarise TOTAL\_SALES per customer and then combine with total\_qty table.}
\NormalTok{sales\_per\_customer }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ data }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(LYLTY\_CARD\_NBR) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{CUSTOMER\_SALES =} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(TOT\_SALES))}
\NormalTok{sales\_per\_customer }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{merge}\NormalTok{(total\_qty, sales\_per\_customer, }\AttributeTok{all.x =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}

\CommentTok{\# add a column that represent price per unit paid bu each customer}
\NormalTok{sales\_per\_unit }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ sales\_per\_customer }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{SPU=}\NormalTok{CUSTOMER\_SALES}\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{TOT\_PROD\_QTY)}

\CommentTok{\# summarise average price per unit by lifestage and premium categories.}
\NormalTok{spu }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ sales\_per\_unit }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(LIFESTAGE, PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{summarise}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{AVG\_SPU=}\FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(SPU))}
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\#\#\#\#\# Plot them}

\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(spu, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{fill=}\NormalTok{PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER, }\AttributeTok{y=}\NormalTok{AVG\_SPU, }\AttributeTok{x=}\NormalTok{LIFESTAGE))  }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
    \FunctionTok{geom\_bar}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{position=}\StringTok{"dodge"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{stat=}\StringTok{"identity"}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{theme}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{axis.text.x =} \FunctionTok{element\_text}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{angle =} \DecValTok{60}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{vjust =} \FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{labs}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =} \StringTok{"Lifestage"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{y =} \StringTok{"Average Price Per Unit"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{title =} \StringTok{"Average Purchase Per Unit by Lifestage and Premium"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{center}\includegraphics{quantium_task_1_files/figure-latex/unnamed-chunk-10-1} \end{center}

Mainstream midage and young singles and couples are more willing to pay
more per packet of chips compared to their budget and premium
counterparts. This may be due to premium shoppers being more likely to
buy healthy snacks and when they buy chips, this is mainly for
entertainment purposes rather than their own consumption. This is also
supported by there being fewer premium midage and young singles and
couples buying chips compared to their mainstream counterparts.

As the difference in average price per unit isn't large, we can check if
this difference is statistically different.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# Perform an independent t{-}test between mainstream vs premium and budget midage and }
\DocumentationTok{\#\#\#\# young singles and couples }

\NormalTok{mainstream }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ (spu }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"Mainstream"} \SpecialCharTok{\&}\NormalTok{ (LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES"}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"MIDAGE SINGLES/COUPLES"}\NormalTok{)))}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{AVG\_SPU}
\NormalTok{budget }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ (spu }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER }\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"Budget"} \SpecialCharTok{\&}\NormalTok{ (LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES"}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"MIDAGE SINGLES/COUPLES"}\NormalTok{)))}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{AVG\_SPU}
\NormalTok{premium }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ (spu }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(PREMIUM\_CUSTOMER }\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"Premium"} \SpecialCharTok{\&}\NormalTok{ (LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"YOUNG SINGLES/COUPLES"}\SpecialCharTok{|}\NormalTok{LIFESTAGE}\SpecialCharTok{==}\StringTok{"MIDAGE SINGLES/COUPLES"}\NormalTok{)))}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{AVG\_SPU}

\FunctionTok{t.test}\NormalTok{(mainstream, budget, }\AttributeTok{var.equal=}\ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mainstream and budget
## t = 5.6461, df = 2, p-value = 0.02997
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.09826073 0.72766117
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  4.096134  3.683173
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{t.test}\NormalTok{(mainstream, premium, }\AttributeTok{var.equal=}\ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  mainstream and premium
## t = 4.6897, df = 2, p-value = 0.04258
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.03331738 0.77398990
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  4.096134  3.692481
\end{verbatim}

The t-test results in a p-value of 0.04258 (0.01667), i.e.~the unit
price for mainstream, young and mid-age singles and couples ARE
significantly higher than that of budget (premium), young and midage
singles and couples.
